\par Erik Erikson had been at the Institute earlier, Glen knew his work, which concerned identity rather than context.  Life course approach is to put people\rquote 
s lives in context.  Dealing with changing identity fits with this, but the concept of generativ
ity is too limiting.  It is useful to build unresolved earlier issues into the perspective of cumulative dis/advantage.  At Berkeley the sociologists were thinking about world issues, helped Glen not just focus on individual experience.
\par 
\par Berkeley staff had
 collected economic data, but they never used it beyond SES.  Jean McFarlane could not believe how well the cohort had done at 40, but did not look at their lives after childhood: e.g. those who went into military gained self-confidence, completed educati
on.  Leading point of life course approach is that lives always lived in historical and spatial contexts.
